# Part 2

## Describe a time when you used your imagination.

One experience that immediately comes to mind was last semester, when I participated in a university innovation competition related to artificial intelligence. Our team needed to design a smart system that could help students improve their study efficiency, but at the beginning we had absolutely no clear direction. That was the moment when I really had to rely on my imagination.

The competition happened around the end of last year. At first, most teams were designing very traditional apps, like simple timetable managers or note-taking platforms. I felt that if we wanted to stand out, we needed a more creative idea rather than just copying existing products.

So I started imagining what learning might look like in the future. Instead of creating another ordinary app, I proposed building an AI assistant that could remember a student’s long-term goals, study habits, and emotional state, almost like a digital companion. For example, if a student kept procrastinating or losing motivation, the system could actively encourage them, adjust study plans, or even remind them to take breaks.

At that stage, the idea sounded a bit unrealistic because we didn’t actually have enough technical skills to fully build such an advanced system. However, imagination helped us create a unique concept and a convincing presentation. I spent a lot of time drawing diagrams, visualizing how users would interact with the AI, and even imagining future scenarios where personalized AI assistants become common in education.

My teammates were initially skeptical, but gradually they became excited about the concept. In the end, although our prototype was relatively simple, the judges appreciated our creativity and future-oriented thinking. We didn’t win first prize, but we received an award for innovation.

I felt extremely satisfied after that experience because I realized imagination is not just for artists or children. In fields like technology and science, imagination is often the starting point of innovation. Without imagination, people would probably never create anything truly new.

---

### 中文翻译：

我立刻想到的一次经历，是上学期我参加学校人工智能创新比赛的时候。当时我们团队需要设计一个帮助学生提高学习效率的智能系统，但一开始我们完全没有明确方向。那也是我真正需要依靠想象力的时候。

比赛大概发生在去年年底。当时大多数队伍做的都是比较传统的软件，比如课程表管理或者笔记类应用。我觉得如果我们想脱颖而出，就必须提出更有创意的想法，而不是单纯复制已有产品。

于是我开始想象未来的学习方式。我提出，与其做一个普通App，不如设计一个能够记住学生长期目标、学习习惯甚至情绪状态的AI助手，就像一个数字伙伴一样。比如当学生拖延或者失去动力时，它可以主动鼓励学生、调整学习计划，甚至提醒休息。

当时这个想法听起来其实有点不现实，因为我们的技术能力还不足以真正做出这么高级的系统。但想象力帮助我们构建了一个独特的概念和很有说服力的展示。我花了很多时间画结构图、想象用户如何与AI互动，甚至设想未来教育中人人都有个性化AI助手的场景。

一开始队友还有些怀疑，但后来大家逐渐对这个想法兴奋起来。最后虽然我们的原型并不复杂，但评委很欣赏我们的创造力和未来视角。我们虽然没有拿一等奖，但获得了创新奖。

这次经历让我特别满足，因为我意识到想象力不仅属于艺术家或小孩子。在科技和科学领域，想象力往往才是创新的起点。如果没有想象力，人类可能永远无法创造真正新的东西。

